1
00:00:14,709 --> 00:00:16,709
Name: Muhannad Mahmoud Saeed

2
00:00:17,125 --> 00:00:18,876
From the right
side of the Old City

3
00:00:19,709 --> 00:00:21,584
Born on April 18, 1993

4
00:00:22,334 --> 00:00:23,751
Married

5
00:00:24,876 --> 00:00:27,209
I work freelance
jobs to make a living

6
00:00:27,959 --> 00:00:30,417
At the time of my arrest, I was
working on a potato machine

7
00:00:33,542 --> 00:00:36,083
They arrested me even
though I had a permit from them

8
00:00:36,500 --> 00:00:39,667
A permit to stay, since it was
during Friday prayer on Eid al-Adha

9
00:00:40,959 --> 00:00:44,209
I got a permit from
them to guard the place

10
00:00:44,792 --> 00:00:47,042
The games and the potato machine

11
00:00:48,042 --> 00:00:51,250
The <i>Hisba</i> [religious police] car
came and saw me selling to children

12
00:00:52,250 --> 00:00:53,834
He called out to me
but I did not notice

13
00:00:54,292 --> 00:00:55,918
He told me to get in
the car and I refused

14
00:00:56,959 --> 00:00:58,584
I told him I have a
permit, and I refused

15
00:00:59,042 --> 00:01:01,125
He pushed me and shoved
me into a Hyundai Starex

16
00:01:02,250 --> 00:01:04,500
There were two people inside

17
00:01:05,959 --> 00:01:07,834
They were also prisoners, and
they brought them along with me

18
00:01:09,584 --> 00:01:12,292
Interviewer: Alright, you said
exactly that it was during Eid

19
00:01:12,292 --> 00:01:13,443
Witness: Yes,
during the major Eid

20
00:01:13,468 --> 00:01:17,959
Interviewer: The potato machine,
was it for your work as a street vendor?

21
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:19,792
Or did you have a fixed
location to sell from?

22
00:01:19,792 --> 00:01:25,125
No, I was standing on
the street next to the games

23
00:01:25,167 --> 00:01:26,751
The machine is mobile

24
00:01:27,334 --> 00:01:29,834
But during Eid I kept it
stationary next to the games

25
00:01:29,959 --> 00:01:32,500
Interviewer: You mean the games are for
children? Witness: Yes, children's games

26
00:01:32,542 --> 00:01:35,115
Interviewer: It was for the Eid
celebration? Witness: Yes, the major Eid

27
00:01:35,334 --> 00:01:39,334
Interviewer: When
exactly was this Eid?

28
00:01:39,584 --> 00:01:41,459
It was in the year
ISIS entered here

29
00:01:41,626 --> 00:01:43,250
Ramadan came
first, then Eid al-Adha

30
00:01:44,209 --> 00:01:46,167
Interviewer: You mean that
was in 2014? Witness: Yes

31
00:01:46,209 --> 00:01:48,667
Interviewer: So at the very beginning of
their arrival? Witness: Yes, at the beginning

32
00:01:49,303 --> 00:01:51,000
Interviewer: Alright, you
said you got permission

33
00:01:51,042 --> 00:01:53,626
From whom did you get permission
to stay and not go to prayer?

34
00:01:53,667 --> 00:01:56,334
From the Hisba, because there were
two of us on the machine, my brother and I

35
00:01:57,042 --> 00:02:00,292
My brother goes to prayer
and when he comes back, I go

36
00:02:01,834 --> 00:02:04,542
The one who gave me the
permit was far away from me

37
00:02:04,667 --> 00:02:06,876
He was heading to the Clock Tower
area, sweeping through the shops

38
00:02:07,876 --> 00:02:09,167
Calling out, To
prayer, to prayer

39
00:02:10,042 --> 00:02:11,834
Then a Starex car
came from a distance

40
00:02:11,876 --> 00:02:12,876
And at that time

41
00:02:13,250 --> 00:02:15,375
Children came to me wanting to
buy as they were heading home

42
00:02:16,459 --> 00:02:19,792
It was forbidden. According to ISIS,
selling during prayer time was prohibited

43
00:02:20,375 --> 00:02:22,792
But I saw they were children who
wanted to go home since it was noon

44
00:02:23,918 --> 00:02:26,083
And as I was selling
to them, they saw me

45
00:02:26,959 --> 00:02:28,417
So they grabbed me

46
00:02:29,626 --> 00:02:31,792
Interviewer: When he
saw you not at prayer

47
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:34,334
And did not know
you had a permit

48
00:02:34,375 --> 00:02:38,167
Alright, after he learned you had
a permit, did he not let you go?

49
00:02:38,167 --> 00:02:40,667
I told him I have a permit.
He said, No, you are selling

50
00:02:41,167 --> 00:02:44,542
I told him I have a permit to
guard the games and the machine

51
00:02:45,042 --> 00:02:46,959
I told him there are
two of us on the machine

52
00:02:47,542 --> 00:02:49,876
He goes to prayer and
when he comes back, I go

53
00:02:49,918 --> 00:02:51,209
It is not the first time

54
00:02:51,542 --> 00:02:54,626
Because during Ramadan we were
selling on the Grand Mosque street

55
00:02:55,250 --> 00:02:56,459
After breaking the fast

56
00:02:57,125 --> 00:02:58,667
During the evening prayer,
one of us stays at the machine

57
00:02:58,667 --> 00:02:59,792
And the other goes to prayer

58
00:03:00,209 --> 00:03:02,334
When my brother comes back
from prayer, he takes my place

59
00:03:02,334 --> 00:03:03,334
And I go to the mosque

60
00:03:04,250 --> 00:03:06,292
Interviewer: He was not convinced?
Witness: No, and he told me to get in

61
00:03:06,709 --> 00:03:09,709
I argued with them, then one
of them came and pushed me

62
00:03:10,500 --> 00:03:11,584
And shoved me into the car

63
00:03:11,667 --> 00:03:13,792
Interviewer: How many
ISIS members arrested you?

64
00:03:13,834 --> 00:03:14,918
There were two in the car

65
00:03:15,834 --> 00:03:17,584
Interviewer: No, I mean
from ISIS members

66
00:03:17,626 --> 00:03:20,542
Yes, the driver and
another person with him

67
00:03:21,626 --> 00:03:23,751
And there were two
prisoners in the car

68
00:03:24,459 --> 00:03:26,959
Interviewer: There were other
prisoners in the car? Witness: Yes, two

69
00:03:27,125 --> 00:03:28,626
Interviewer: So you
became three? Witness: Yes

70
00:03:28,626 --> 00:03:30,500
Interviewer: And only two
ISIS members? Witness: Yes

71
00:03:30,959 --> 00:03:33,459
Interviewer: Alright,
during the car ride

72
00:03:33,500 --> 00:03:35,876
From the place of arrest
until they took you to the prison

73
00:03:36,375 --> 00:03:40,834
Did it not cross your minds to free yourselves
since you were three and they were two?

74
00:03:41,375 --> 00:03:44,626
We could not, because the road
was full of their cars coming and going

75
00:03:44,667 --> 00:03:46,042
And they were spread
out all over the street

76
00:03:46,959 --> 00:03:50,250
At first, they took us from
the Saraj Khana intersection

77
00:03:50,959 --> 00:03:53,667
The Saraj Khana intersection
had one of their posts

78
00:03:54,542 --> 00:03:58,133
And there is the other intersection,
the Shaarin Market intersection

79
00:03:58,158 --> 00:04:03,292
That was also their post,
and this was their main street

80
00:04:03,292 --> 00:04:04,834
Where the Hisba and
others were, all of them here

81
00:04:05,167 --> 00:04:07,375
They were heavily
deployed on this street

82
00:04:08,584 --> 00:04:12,209
Interviewer: The two people
arrested before you who were in the car

83
00:04:12,709 --> 00:04:14,918
Where were they arrested from? Do
you remember what their charges were?

84
00:04:15,042 --> 00:04:17,000
One of them was brought
from Bab al-Sham gate

85
00:04:17,918 --> 00:04:18,918
He was at a wedding procession

86
00:04:20,250 --> 00:04:22,459
Interviewer: You mean he
had a wedding procession?

87
00:04:22,500 --> 00:04:24,125
He was participating
in a wedding procession

88
00:04:25,667 --> 00:04:27,334
Interviewer: You mean at a
wedding? Witness: Yes, a wedding

89
00:04:27,459 --> 00:04:31,792
At Bab al-Sham gate
they pulled him out of a car

90
00:04:31,834 --> 00:04:35,083
He had shaved his
beard and drawn it in

91
00:04:35,918 --> 00:04:38,542
And the other person was
for something related to prayer

92
00:04:39,209 --> 00:04:42,667
No, they did not
blindfold us or tie us up

93
00:04:42,709 --> 00:04:47,292
But he kept saying that their
conquests were delayed because of us

94
00:04:47,667 --> 00:04:50,250
They no longer had conquests,
and I do not know either

95
00:04:50,626 --> 00:04:53,500
Because you are not cooperating
and you are neglecting prayer

96
00:04:53,500 --> 00:04:56,959
And you do not support us.
That is the kind of talk they used

97
00:04:57,250 --> 00:04:58,626
Interviewer: What did
he mean by conquests?

98
00:04:58,667 --> 00:05:03,542
Meaning they wanted to
conquer Baghdad, to reach it

99
00:05:03,876 --> 00:05:07,042
Reaching Baghdad was like the devil
dreaming of paradise, as the saying goes

100
00:05:08,125 --> 00:05:10,918
Interviewer: You mean he was telling you that
because of you they could not achieve victory?

101
00:05:10,959 --> 00:05:12,542
Yes, they could not
achieve victory because of us

102
00:05:12,542 --> 00:05:16,751
And another thing, they
believed they could conquer Rome

103
00:05:19,626 --> 00:05:22,918
Interviewer: You mean they
blamed you for their losses in battle

104
00:05:23,000 --> 00:05:25,250
Because you do
not perform prayers?

105
00:05:25,500 --> 00:05:29,125
Yes, they would say God does
not grant us success because of you

106
00:05:30,292 --> 00:05:33,083
You do not pray, you do not
help us, you do not pray for us

107
00:05:33,352 --> 00:05:35,334
Interviewer: This conversation
was inside the car? Witness: Yes

108
00:05:35,375 --> 00:05:38,250
Interviewer: Did you or
any of the people with you try

109
00:05:38,292 --> 00:05:40,292
To respond to them
or argue with them?

110
00:05:40,334 --> 00:05:44,918
You cannot respond to them

111
00:05:50,417 --> 00:05:53,209
Interviewer: Alright, when they
brought you to the prison by car

112
00:05:53,292 --> 00:05:57,500
And since these are old neighborhoods with
narrow alleys that cars cannot pass through

113
00:05:57,542 --> 00:05:59,000
Where exactly did
they stop the car?

114
00:05:59,042 --> 00:06:00,459
And how did they march
you to the prison gate?

115
00:06:00,792 --> 00:06:04,584
There is a square
near the Biya church

116
00:06:05,542 --> 00:06:06,542
There is a square there

117
00:06:07,083 --> 00:06:08,918
He drove the car all the way
in, and they made us get out

118
00:06:09,334 --> 00:06:11,751
In the square, and you
know this area is considered

119
00:06:12,500 --> 00:06:14,167
A military zone
belonging to them

120
00:06:14,334 --> 00:06:16,500
This means no one could escape

121
00:06:17,125 --> 00:06:19,292
Because they were heavily
present in this area in particular

122
00:06:19,375 --> 00:06:21,626
Interviewer: Why did they make
this particular area a military zone?

123
00:06:21,626 --> 00:06:26,375
Because they seized the churches
belonging to our Christian brothers

124
00:06:27,292 --> 00:06:29,417
They seized the
opportunity and took them

125
00:06:29,459 --> 00:06:31,709
And turned them into
prisons and sharia courts

126
00:06:31,959 --> 00:06:34,542
Interviewer: You mean because most
of this area's residents were Christians?

127
00:06:34,584 --> 00:06:35,834
Yes, because most
residents were Christians

128
00:06:35,859 --> 00:06:37,405
Interviewer: And they
took their money and homes

129
00:06:37,465 --> 00:06:38,731
Yes, they took everything

130
00:06:38,834 --> 00:06:41,167
And not only from Christians
but from Muslims too

131
00:06:41,209 --> 00:06:43,250
They took their money
and seized their homes

132
00:06:43,375 --> 00:06:44,959
Interviewer: I mean
why this particular area?

133
00:06:44,959 --> 00:06:48,709
This area specifically because it
belonged to our Christian brothers

134
00:06:49,459 --> 00:06:53,417
Interviewer: So they brought you
to the square near the Biya church

135
00:06:53,459 --> 00:06:56,667
After that, how did they treat you
until they brought you to the prison?

136
00:06:57,500 --> 00:06:58,834
They made us walk in a
line, one behind the other

137
00:06:59,334 --> 00:07:00,959
One of them in front of
us and another behind us

138
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:02,959
And two of them on the sides,
and they brought us from this road

139
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:06,042
From there until
they took us inside

140
00:07:06,042 --> 00:07:09,209
Interviewer: How far was
the distance you had to walk?

141
00:07:09,250 --> 00:07:11,000
How far in meters, for
example 100 or 200 meters?

142
00:07:11,042 --> 00:07:12,709
It was not a long distance

143
00:07:12,792 --> 00:07:16,125
From this road, then that
one, in the Biya church square

144
00:07:16,209 --> 00:07:17,959
Interviewer: Did they leave your
eyes uncovered? Witness: Yes

145
00:07:17,959 --> 00:07:19,709
Interviewer: And your hands
too? Witness: Yes, the same

146
00:07:19,751 --> 00:07:22,751
Interviewer: Alright, as you were passing
through the square where the car stopped

147
00:07:22,751 --> 00:07:25,209
Until they brought
you to the church gate

148
00:07:25,209 --> 00:07:27,751
Which was the second
prison they put you in

149
00:07:27,834 --> 00:07:32,542
Was it normal for people
around to look at you?

150
00:07:32,584 --> 00:07:34,209
Yes, it was normal

151
00:07:34,250 --> 00:07:36,959
But it was a Friday
and it was Eid

152
00:07:37,667 --> 00:07:39,918
There were not
many people around

153
00:07:40,334 --> 00:07:43,834
Only children and
young men were around

154
00:07:44,125 --> 00:07:47,375
Interviewer: So they did not direct
abusive language at you or humiliate you

155
00:07:47,751 --> 00:07:51,959
Interviewer: Did you not feel humiliated
when they marched you like this?

156
00:07:51,959 --> 00:07:53,834
Yes, of course

157
00:07:53,876 --> 00:07:56,584
Interviewer: Describe
the feeling you had

158
00:07:56,584 --> 00:08:00,876
I was walking as if I were a
criminal, yet I had done nothing

159
00:08:01,250 --> 00:08:02,417
According to them,
I was a criminal

160
00:08:03,417 --> 00:08:06,417
As if I had committed something
terrible, yet I had done nothing wrong

161
00:08:07,125 --> 00:08:13,709
Why would they make me walk in
front of people like a captive, powerless?

162
00:08:15,042 --> 00:08:16,918
Interviewer: You mean you
felt humiliated? Witness: Yes

163
00:08:18,209 --> 00:08:20,792
It is a feeling I
cannot describe

164
00:08:21,709 --> 00:08:26,334
They were the scum of society,
and now they controlled us

165
00:08:27,167 --> 00:08:29,709
Interviewer: So the
people who arrested you

166
00:08:30,083 --> 00:08:34,709
Can you describe their
appearance, ages, and dialects?

167
00:08:34,959 --> 00:08:39,584
Were they from the city of
Mosul, the outskirts, or the villages?

168
00:08:39,667 --> 00:08:41,709
Were they from other governorates
or were they of other nationalities?

169
00:08:42,459 --> 00:08:46,876
No, they were from Mosul, its
outskirts, and from the villages

170
00:08:47,375 --> 00:08:48,667
Their dialect was not
the Mosul city dialect

171
00:08:50,167 --> 00:08:51,709
Interviewer: Describe their
appearance and approximate ages

172
00:08:54,584 --> 00:08:58,167
They were roughly
in their twenties

173
00:08:59,125 --> 00:09:04,250
Because an older, aware person
would know their true nature

174
00:09:04,375 --> 00:09:07,626
They did have older
people among them

175
00:09:07,709 --> 00:09:11,292
But they had joined their ideology from
the beginning, believing they were right

176
00:09:11,834 --> 00:09:16,918
But among the newer recruits, there
were not many older knowledgeable men

177
00:09:16,959 --> 00:09:18,918
Men of knowledge
and understanding

178
00:09:19,334 --> 00:09:20,834
Rather, those who
joined them were ignorant

179
00:09:21,292 --> 00:09:23,584
And those who had no work

180
00:09:23,959 --> 00:09:26,459
And those who took
pride in carrying weapons

181
00:09:26,876 --> 00:09:28,834
And the result was what happened

182
00:09:29,584 --> 00:09:32,667
Interviewer: Were they
masked when they arrested you?

183
00:09:33,292 --> 00:09:34,959
No, they were not wearing masks

184
00:09:34,959 --> 00:09:37,125
When they first arrived,
they were masked

185
00:09:37,167 --> 00:09:38,959
When they attacked Mosul

186
00:09:39,667 --> 00:09:41,959
But after that, they
removed their masks

187
00:09:43,292 --> 00:09:45,250
Interviewer: So they
brought you to the prison gate

188
00:09:45,250 --> 00:09:47,209
After that, did they
enter the prison with you?

189
00:09:47,209 --> 00:09:48,626
Or did they hand you
over to other people?

190
00:09:48,667 --> 00:09:50,959
No, they brought us to the
gate and others took over

191
00:09:51,417 --> 00:09:53,834
And they closed the church door

192
00:09:58,209 --> 00:10:02,959
Interviewer: When you entered
the church that served as a prison

193
00:10:03,959 --> 00:10:08,334
How did they treat you and
what was their approach?

194
00:10:08,375 --> 00:10:11,584
Did they take you
directly to the prison hall?

195
00:10:11,834 --> 00:10:15,334
Or was there an interrogation,
recording of information and details?

196
00:10:15,375 --> 00:10:17,083
How did they handle
your personal belongings?

197
00:10:17,459 --> 00:10:21,876
And what kind of
questions did they ask you?

198
00:10:22,834 --> 00:10:23,959
When we first entered

199
00:10:24,626 --> 00:10:26,500
The person told the other
that this one neglected prayer

200
00:10:26,500 --> 00:10:27,918
And that one was brought from
a wedding and was clean-shaven

201
00:10:28,959 --> 00:10:31,834
When he heard that one of us neglected prayer and
the other was clean-shaven, he lost his temper

202
00:10:31,834 --> 00:10:33,542
As if I had committed
something terrible

203
00:10:34,042 --> 00:10:35,959
I swore to him that I
was not neglecting prayer

204
00:10:37,209 --> 00:10:39,250
He said, Yes you are. Get inside

205
00:10:39,792 --> 00:10:41,500
They recorded our information
and took our belongings

206
00:10:41,876 --> 00:10:43,375
And during the search,
they found cigarettes on me

207
00:10:44,542 --> 00:10:46,959
Interviewer: Where were the cigarettes?
Witness: I was keeping them here

208
00:10:48,042 --> 00:10:49,459
I was wearing pants at the time

209
00:10:51,292 --> 00:10:54,167
I was keeping cigarettes here, one
pack for me and one for my brother

210
00:10:54,959 --> 00:10:57,417
Interviewer: After they found
cigarettes on you, how did they treat you?

211
00:10:58,626 --> 00:11:00,959
They shouted and pushed me

212
00:11:01,334 --> 00:11:02,792
And asked me where I got them

213
00:11:02,792 --> 00:11:06,292
I told them they were mine, from a
while ago when I was working in the market

214
00:11:06,375 --> 00:11:08,792
I had stocked up, and
this was what remained

215
00:11:11,834 --> 00:11:14,459
Interviewer: And what happened
after that, after you went in?

216
00:11:14,500 --> 00:11:16,292
They recorded
information like full name

217
00:11:16,292 --> 00:11:18,250
Mother's name, and
place of residence

218
00:11:20,209 --> 00:11:22,375
He took me inside. I told him I was not
neglecting prayer and that I had a permit

219
00:11:22,375 --> 00:11:23,834
He said, No, you
are neglecting prayer

220
00:11:23,834 --> 00:11:25,876
He pushed me and
shoved me into the hall

221
00:11:25,959 --> 00:11:28,250
Interviewer: Alright, the person
who recorded your information

222
00:11:28,292 --> 00:11:33,083
Do you think this man
knew you from before?

223
00:11:33,709 --> 00:11:35,959
Interviewer: Or you did not know
him? Witness: No, I did not know him

224
00:11:36,334 --> 00:11:38,334
Interviewer: How old was he
approximately? What did he look like?

225
00:11:38,542 --> 00:11:41,500
He was about 30 or 28 years old

226
00:11:41,542 --> 00:11:43,250
Dark-skinned with a black beard

227
00:11:43,792 --> 00:11:46,334
Wearing the Qandahari
outfit and the Hisba robe

228
00:11:47,792 --> 00:11:51,292
Interviewer: Was this person
specifically assigned to this task?

229
00:11:51,334 --> 00:11:54,417
Or could any one of
them take the information?

230
00:11:55,209 --> 00:11:56,959
There was a person
sitting at the table

231
00:11:57,918 --> 00:12:01,083
He recorded the information,
then took the notebook and left

232
00:12:01,542 --> 00:12:03,000
He went to that church

233
00:12:03,083 --> 00:12:05,626
To the main computer to enter
the information, I do not know

234
00:12:07,125 --> 00:12:09,876
Interviewer: Then where did they send
you? Witness: They sent us to the hall

235
00:12:10,876 --> 00:12:13,792
We stayed in the hall, and
when afternoon prayer time came

236
00:12:14,918 --> 00:12:16,792
They brought us in here

237
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:18,167
I performed ablution here

238
00:12:19,042 --> 00:12:22,584
We prayed the afternoon prayer,
then about an hour after prayer

239
00:12:22,626 --> 00:12:26,667
They brought us all out
and divided us into groups

240
00:12:26,709 --> 00:12:28,459
They took us
upstairs to that room

241
00:12:33,042 --> 00:12:37,334
They took us upstairs, and when
you looked at the prisoners there

242
00:12:37,876 --> 00:12:42,584
This one was there for smoking, that one
for fighting, another for missing prayer

243
00:12:43,751 --> 00:12:45,375
You look at it as
a tragic situation

244
00:12:46,876 --> 00:12:50,542
There was no fear of being there

245
00:12:50,709 --> 00:12:53,834
The fear was only from a possible
attack, bombing, or something like that

246
00:12:54,209 --> 00:12:57,334
Then you would disappear,
and no one would know about you

247
00:12:57,834 --> 00:12:59,500
Because they did not provide
you with any information

248
00:12:59,959 --> 00:13:03,584
When they came to the Hisba
looking for me, they did not tell them

249
00:13:03,626 --> 00:13:06,292
When they came asking there, they said, We do
not have anyone. We did not bring anyone here

250
00:13:07,042 --> 00:13:11,542
And that went on until the
afternoon, until you found one of them

251
00:13:11,584 --> 00:13:14,959
And you asked him and
begged him to give you a lead

252
00:13:15,959 --> 00:13:19,292
In the hall you could not
talk because security was tight

253
00:13:19,334 --> 00:13:23,167
You never knew. One of their members
could be planted and sitting among you

254
00:13:23,292 --> 00:13:25,000
Gathering information and such

255
00:13:25,292 --> 00:13:28,292
You could not speak.
Everyone sat in a corner

256
00:13:28,334 --> 00:13:31,250
Or if you had a friend inside,
you sat with him in a corner

257
00:13:31,292 --> 00:13:34,167
No one could mix
with the others at first

258
00:13:34,167 --> 00:13:36,542
Because you did not know the
true identity of those around you

259
00:13:37,959 --> 00:13:42,667
And they did not provide water
or food. They gave us nothing

260
00:13:43,500 --> 00:13:45,584
There was one of them
who led the prayers

261
00:13:45,584 --> 00:13:48,459
And they focused specifically
on the supplication prayer

262
00:13:50,959 --> 00:13:53,626
They prayed over us, God,
deal with the oppressors

263
00:13:53,626 --> 00:13:55,250
God, deal with the apostates

264
00:13:55,250 --> 00:13:57,167
God, deal with America

265
00:13:57,209 --> 00:13:59,667
And other supplications

266
00:13:59,792 --> 00:14:01,709
They did not realize this
prayer would come back on them

267
00:14:02,626 --> 00:14:06,459
Interviewer: Can you describe
the hall and what was in it?

268
00:14:06,792 --> 00:14:08,542
The furniture inside it?

269
00:14:08,918 --> 00:14:13,918
The bedding, curtains and
their colors, the wall color?

270
00:14:14,417 --> 00:14:16,626
Can you describe the
smell of the place itself?

271
00:14:17,042 --> 00:14:19,459
The place is currently destroyed

272
00:14:19,667 --> 00:14:22,083
But previously it
was clean and tidy

273
00:14:22,083 --> 00:14:24,959
And carpeted with red carpet

274
00:14:25,626 --> 00:14:28,417
Striped carpet
like mosque carpet

275
00:14:29,751 --> 00:14:31,876
And there were Qurans

276
00:14:31,918 --> 00:14:33,167
And it was lit and painted

277
00:14:33,209 --> 00:14:36,834
The place was clean
and well organized

278
00:14:38,542 --> 00:14:40,500
Interviewer: You entered
this place without shoes?

279
00:14:40,542 --> 00:14:43,959
No, without shoes. You take off
your shoes at the stairs and enter

280
00:14:45,334 --> 00:14:50,375
Interviewer: Describe to me, was there
one of their flags hanging on the walls?

281
00:14:50,626 --> 00:14:53,542
A wall clock for example,
or any of their slogans?

282
00:14:53,709 --> 00:14:55,959
Their slogans and flags
were hung everywhere

283
00:14:56,125 --> 00:14:57,792
Here a flag hanging,
and there another

284
00:14:58,167 --> 00:14:59,918
And I think inside
there was a flag too

285
00:15:00,500 --> 00:15:04,209
And there was a place closed off by a
curtain. We did not know what was behind it

286
00:15:05,626 --> 00:15:08,709
We were sitting until just before
sunset, then they took us upstairs

287
00:15:09,167 --> 00:15:12,292
Interviewer: The hall
they first put you in

288
00:15:12,334 --> 00:15:15,125
Do you remember what it was
used for inside the church before?

289
00:15:15,125 --> 00:15:16,792
No, I had never
entered it before

290
00:15:17,876 --> 00:15:20,584
The first time I
entered this hall

291
00:15:22,250 --> 00:15:23,667
Was during ISIS's time

292
00:15:23,751 --> 00:15:27,042
But before that, we used to pass by here
since we are from these neighborhoods

293
00:15:27,083 --> 00:15:29,792
When we went to the river,
we passed in front of the church

294
00:15:30,083 --> 00:15:31,334
But we did not know
what was inside it

295
00:15:31,709 --> 00:15:34,125
Interviewer: Alright,
inside the hall

296
00:15:34,667 --> 00:15:39,500
Were you allowed to talk
among yourselves freely?

297
00:15:40,042 --> 00:15:41,417
You could not talk freely

298
00:15:41,459 --> 00:15:43,959
If you spoke and
raised your voice a little

299
00:15:44,500 --> 00:15:47,626
He would immediately shout
from outside, Quiet. No one talks

300
00:15:48,250 --> 00:15:49,292
Do not make any noise

301
00:15:51,125 --> 00:15:53,417
Interviewer: When you
first entered the prison

302
00:15:53,459 --> 00:15:55,500
When they took your
information and belongings

303
00:15:55,500 --> 00:15:58,042
And put you in this hall as
a temporary prison at first

304
00:15:58,542 --> 00:16:02,959
During all this time, did you not hear
prisoners being tortured and screaming?

305
00:16:03,417 --> 00:16:07,167
Did you not hear anything
suspicious or strange sounds?

306
00:16:07,209 --> 00:16:09,542
Did you not hear any
women's voices, for example?

307
00:16:10,334 --> 00:16:12,751
No, severe torture
did not happen here

308
00:16:15,000 --> 00:16:17,834
Severe torture happened when a
person was tried or did not confess

309
00:16:19,417 --> 00:16:22,542
Would not confess, for example,
that he sold or traded cigarettes

310
00:16:22,959 --> 00:16:26,459
Or for taking sedative pills

311
00:16:26,959 --> 00:16:28,459
And most of them
were taking them

312
00:16:28,542 --> 00:16:31,417
Pills like Tisirom and
others, and their needles

313
00:16:32,584 --> 00:16:34,125
And there is a torture method
called <i>hantoura</i> [bed-like contraption]

314
00:16:35,500 --> 00:16:40,918
With it, you would confess
even if you had done nothing

315
00:16:41,042 --> 00:16:42,709
Interviewer: Was there
a hantoura in this place?

316
00:16:42,709 --> 00:16:45,000
No, not in this place.
In another location

317
00:16:50,709 --> 00:16:54,375
We were about 20 or more
people in the room, upstairs

318
00:16:54,667 --> 00:16:58,375
In this small room,
roughly three by four meters

319
00:17:00,626 --> 00:17:04,667
We sat next to each other,
leaning on one another

320
00:17:06,042 --> 00:17:07,083
We just sat there doing nothing

321
00:17:07,417 --> 00:17:13,667
Interviewer: Was there inside the room
mattresses or foam for sleeping and blankets?

322
00:17:13,792 --> 00:17:14,918
There was no foam

323
00:17:15,334 --> 00:17:17,667
The floor was just carpeted

324
00:17:18,500 --> 00:17:20,375
Interviewer: Carpeted with
what? Witness: With carpet

325
00:17:21,542 --> 00:17:24,125
Interviewer: You mean you
also entered without shoes?

326
00:17:25,083 --> 00:17:26,876
Yes, we took off our
shoes and entered

327
00:17:27,834 --> 00:17:33,250
Interviewer: Were there curtains
and windows in this room?

328
00:17:33,626 --> 00:17:37,918
All the windows were
closed and sealed with iron

329
00:17:37,918 --> 00:17:40,584
As you saw, they
were all sealed with iron

330
00:17:41,334 --> 00:17:44,167
There was only a small opening
that let in some light and air

331
00:17:44,918 --> 00:17:46,792
Interviewer: When
you entered this room

332
00:17:46,876 --> 00:17:49,751
Did you expect to find this
number of prisoners with you?

333
00:17:50,876 --> 00:17:51,876
No, I did not expect it

334
00:17:51,876 --> 00:17:54,167
When I entered, I was
shocked that this small room

335
00:17:54,209 --> 00:17:56,292
Had more than 20 people in it

336
00:17:57,042 --> 00:18:01,500
Can you imagine what the air would
be like from everyone breathing?

337
00:18:04,167 --> 00:18:06,542
Interviewer: What were
their approximate ages?

338
00:18:06,542 --> 00:18:09,375
From the youngest to the
oldest prisoner in this room

339
00:18:09,417 --> 00:18:12,334
And can you tell me what
exactly were their charges?

340
00:18:12,375 --> 00:18:13,834
Most of them were young men

341
00:18:13,876 --> 00:18:17,959
This one for smoking, that
one for being late to prayer

342
00:18:17,959 --> 00:18:20,083
That one for shaving his
beard, others for fighting

343
00:18:21,083 --> 00:18:22,709
They were of average young age

344
00:18:22,751 --> 00:18:27,250
And some were older,
about 30 or 35 or less

345
00:18:27,626 --> 00:18:29,292
Interviewer: You mean
there were no elderly people?

346
00:18:29,292 --> 00:18:30,584
No, there were no elderly people

347
00:18:30,959 --> 00:18:33,042
Interviewer: You mean the
oldest person was about 40?

348
00:18:33,042 --> 00:18:34,417
Yes, approximately

349
00:18:38,792 --> 00:18:40,209
When I first entered

350
00:18:41,083 --> 00:18:42,459
The situation was tragic

351
00:18:42,500 --> 00:18:49,459
You became a criminal in
their eyes for something trivial

352
00:18:50,250 --> 00:18:52,792
As if you committed a
crime over something trivial

353
00:18:52,834 --> 00:18:56,250
When you saw the situation before
you, it caused psychological distress

354
00:18:57,334 --> 00:19:01,375
Some had been there four days,
others three, and others five days

355
00:19:01,876 --> 00:19:05,375
And that was for minor issues

356
00:19:05,918 --> 00:19:07,959
And there were worse cases

357
00:19:08,417 --> 00:19:10,417
Some of them died
under torture at their hands

358
00:19:11,250 --> 00:19:13,209
Interviewer: In this prison?
Witness: No, in another prison

359
00:19:13,209 --> 00:19:17,417
The torture here was not considered
severe. There was flogging and such

360
00:19:17,792 --> 00:19:19,459
When they transferred
you to another place

361
00:19:20,918 --> 00:19:22,542
Then suffering was
written for you by God

362
00:19:23,500 --> 00:19:26,667
Interviewer: Alright, from the
beginning when you entered the hall

363
00:19:26,709 --> 00:19:29,459
Then they transferred
you to the room

364
00:19:29,500 --> 00:19:33,417
And in between, you
went out for ablution

365
00:19:33,918 --> 00:19:35,751
Did it not cross
your mind to escape?

366
00:19:36,667 --> 00:19:38,250
Yes, it crossed my mind

367
00:19:38,792 --> 00:19:42,918
I looked around hoping
to find a way to escape

368
00:19:43,584 --> 00:19:45,000
And since I am from this area

369
00:19:45,417 --> 00:19:50,500
I could escape over the rooftops of houses
and come down from any house to the street

370
00:19:51,292 --> 00:19:53,709
But when I looked, I found
it too difficult, very difficult

371
00:19:53,751 --> 00:19:56,542
You could not because
first, they were armed

372
00:19:57,792 --> 00:20:03,417
And second, he could kill you
easily without caring about you

373
00:20:04,709 --> 00:20:07,209
As if he killed a cockroach

374
00:20:08,709 --> 00:20:11,876
Interviewer: Did you hear of
a prisoner who tried to escape

375
00:20:11,918 --> 00:20:14,542
And they tried to kill him or did kill
him? Did you hear of such a case?

376
00:20:14,542 --> 00:20:19,042
Not only in this prison but in
general, during your life under ISIS?

377
00:20:19,209 --> 00:20:22,417
Yes, there was a case
of a person who escaped

378
00:20:23,709 --> 00:20:26,626
He did not escape from
the prison but from the car

379
00:20:26,751 --> 00:20:28,834
They chased him and
could not catch him

380
00:20:28,876 --> 00:20:31,042
So they opened fire
on him and killed him

381
00:20:32,042 --> 00:20:36,500
Interviewer: How was their
relationship with the victim's family?

382
00:20:36,959 --> 00:20:40,542
Were they forced to keep
silent about his killing?

383
00:20:40,584 --> 00:20:43,125
Or did they give
them blood money?

384
00:20:43,209 --> 00:20:46,167
They were forced to keep
silent. No one could talk to them

385
00:20:46,876 --> 00:20:49,500
The simplest thing for them was
killing. It was the simplest thing

386
00:20:51,334 --> 00:20:55,584
Interviewer: Did any of them
point a weapon at you? Witness: No

387
00:20:56,209 --> 00:20:59,542
Interviewer: Did they not point weapons
at other prisoners who were present?

388
00:21:00,667 --> 00:21:04,709
Interviewer: When he argued with
them or debated them, for example

389
00:21:04,918 --> 00:21:06,209
Witness: No one
could argue with them

390
00:21:07,459 --> 00:21:10,167
Even if you were right, you
could not argue with them

391
00:21:10,807 --> 00:21:12,500
Interviewer: You say no
one could argue with them

392
00:21:12,500 --> 00:21:19,667
And as a young man, was the reason you did
not argue out of fear from within yourselves?

393
00:21:19,918 --> 00:21:22,959
Or did you think arguing
with them was useless?

394
00:21:23,042 --> 00:21:25,500
Arguing with them was
useless, and I am telling you

395
00:21:26,042 --> 00:21:27,542
You feared losing your life

396
00:21:27,959 --> 00:21:29,959
At the hands of people
who are scum, worth nothing

397
00:21:30,751 --> 00:21:32,834
He would kill you, and that
was the simplest thing for him

398
00:21:38,125 --> 00:21:39,959
Everyone here was Arab

399
00:21:40,584 --> 00:21:41,626
There were no others among them

400
00:21:41,834 --> 00:21:43,542
Interviewer: By Arabs, you
mean they held Arab nationalities?

401
00:21:43,542 --> 00:21:46,542
Meaning they were
from Iraq, Iraqis

402
00:21:47,959 --> 00:21:51,959
And most of them were
from the outskirts of Mosul

403
00:21:52,125 --> 00:21:54,292
Interviewer: From the villages? Witness:
From the villages and surrounding areas

404
00:21:54,959 --> 00:21:58,209
I personally did not see anyone
among them from Mosul city

405
00:21:59,500 --> 00:22:03,584
Interviewer: You did not
see? Or there were none at all?

406
00:22:03,626 --> 00:22:08,250
There were people from Mosul,
but not from our neighborhoods

407
00:22:08,250 --> 00:22:11,792
Rather from areas like
Rajm Hadid and Hay al-Tank

408
00:22:13,125 --> 00:22:14,667
And areas even farther away

409
00:22:15,209 --> 00:22:20,500
But I did not see anyone from
the original residents of Mosul

410
00:22:21,125 --> 00:22:24,125
As I told you, whoever argued
with them and pushed further

411
00:22:25,667 --> 00:22:27,542
They dealt with him differently

412
00:22:27,584 --> 00:22:28,709
That is why you could not speak

413
00:22:28,751 --> 00:22:31,292
Whatever he told you, you had
to say yes, alright, you are right

414
00:22:31,751 --> 00:22:33,459
You were expected to listen

415
00:22:34,209 --> 00:22:36,584
Their words went in
one ear and out the other

416
00:22:36,834 --> 00:22:38,584
Because he would sit
there preaching to you

417
00:22:38,876 --> 00:22:42,542
Urging you and asking you
to pledge allegiance to them

418
00:22:42,959 --> 00:22:45,626
You would look at him and think to
yourself, This is a prophet sent from heaven

419
00:22:50,209 --> 00:22:53,042
Interviewer: Did they ask you to
pledge allegiance while in prison?

420
00:22:53,042 --> 00:22:56,167
Personally, they
did not ask me here

421
00:22:57,042 --> 00:22:58,876
I had a situation
at the hospital

422
00:22:59,959 --> 00:23:02,292
At that time, my
daughter had a seizure

423
00:23:04,792 --> 00:23:06,584
And her treatment
was by injection

424
00:23:06,959 --> 00:23:09,584
I had her examined and she
was diagnosed with meningitis

425
00:23:10,209 --> 00:23:13,209
The injection was expensive
because it was rare during ISIS's time

426
00:23:14,375 --> 00:23:16,584
The doctor told me there
were injections available

427
00:23:16,626 --> 00:23:18,292
In their internal pharmacy

428
00:23:19,167 --> 00:23:22,125
Go down to them and see
if they will give you some

429
00:23:24,334 --> 00:23:25,334
I went down to them

430
00:23:25,792 --> 00:23:28,626
Their official was sitting there

431
00:23:29,959 --> 00:23:31,250
I greeted him and he
returned the greeting

432
00:23:32,334 --> 00:23:33,918
I told him, Sheikh, my
situation is such and such

433
00:23:34,334 --> 00:23:37,083
This is my daughter and her
treatment is injections available here

434
00:23:38,209 --> 00:23:39,542
He said, Yes

435
00:23:39,959 --> 00:23:41,167
Are you one of the brothers?

436
00:23:42,209 --> 00:23:43,209
I said, No

437
00:23:43,209 --> 00:23:46,000
Interviewer: What did he mean by the
brothers? Witness: Meaning their group

438
00:23:46,042 --> 00:23:48,959
Interviewer: Meaning ISIS members?
Witness: Yes, they called them brothers

439
00:23:50,125 --> 00:23:51,417
He asked me, Are you
a supporter? I said, No

440
00:23:51,876 --> 00:23:53,709
He said, Then we
will not give you any

441
00:23:54,918 --> 00:23:56,751
I told him these injections
are available here

442
00:23:56,751 --> 00:23:58,959
This is an emergency,
and I have no money

443
00:23:59,292 --> 00:24:01,250
You know during
ISIS, a person worked

444
00:24:02,209 --> 00:24:04,250
Just to get enough for
his family's daily food

445
00:24:06,125 --> 00:24:07,876
He said, Pledge allegiance and
then we will give you the treatment

446
00:24:10,375 --> 00:24:12,876
I looked at him and said, You
want me to pledge allegiance?

447
00:24:14,209 --> 00:24:17,292
I told him she is a small
child, eight months old

448
00:24:17,834 --> 00:24:19,375
If God has decreed
that she should die

449
00:24:20,500 --> 00:24:22,167
Then God will take
back what is His

450
00:24:22,417 --> 00:24:24,792
I told him, Do you want me to
lose my entire clan and my brothers?

451
00:24:24,792 --> 00:24:26,042
Just to get injections?

452
00:24:26,083 --> 00:24:27,792
If God has decreed death
for my daughter, she will die

453
00:24:27,792 --> 00:24:29,125
And if He has decreed
life for her, she will live

454
00:24:29,751 --> 00:24:32,042
He said, What are you saying? Seek God's
forgiveness. I said, I swear, as I told you

455
00:24:32,417 --> 00:24:34,918
And if you want to execute me,
then do it and rid me of this life

456
00:24:35,459 --> 00:24:36,500
I left him and walked out

457
00:24:41,626 --> 00:24:43,167
Interviewer: Alright,
the ISIS members

458
00:24:43,209 --> 00:24:48,626
The cigarettes they took from you or
from others or from cigarette dealers

459
00:24:49,209 --> 00:24:51,959
Did they destroy them or
take them somewhere else?

460
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:53,042
They sold them

461
00:24:53,417 --> 00:24:56,667
Interviewer: They themselves? Witness:
Yes, the members themselves sold them

462
00:24:58,292 --> 00:25:03,334
They sold them. Let us say for
example from here they confiscated

463
00:25:03,792 --> 00:25:06,000
Five or six boxes

464
00:25:06,751 --> 00:25:07,959
They distributed them
among themselves

465
00:25:08,709 --> 00:25:11,417
And sold them. They went back
to the market to be sold again

466
00:25:11,626 --> 00:25:15,459
Interviewer: Are you saying this from
knowledge and experience or is it speculation?

467
00:25:15,792 --> 00:25:19,042
No, from experience. There were people
who bought cigarettes from ISIS members

468
00:25:19,792 --> 00:25:21,834
Interviewer: You mean they
sold cigarettes? Witness: Yes

469
00:25:21,876 --> 00:25:24,462
Interviewer: And they were the ones banning them?
Witness: They used to buy from me and smoke them

470
00:25:25,459 --> 00:25:28,125
Interviewer: Basically,
they had the ban as a rule

471
00:25:28,125 --> 00:25:30,375
Interviewer: The ban was on the basis that
it was forbidden Witness: It is forbidden

472
00:25:30,459 --> 00:25:32,667
Interviewer: They ban
cigarettes yet they seek them out?

473
00:25:32,667 --> 00:25:35,334
Yes, they sold them. They confiscated
them from you and sold them to another

474
00:25:36,209 --> 00:25:40,167
And they sent another group
to confiscate them from him

475
00:25:40,834 --> 00:25:45,000
Interviewer: Do you have a specific case of
an ISIS member selling or buying cigarettes?

476
00:25:45,125 --> 00:25:46,834
Yes, they used to
buy cigarettes from me

477
00:25:47,500 --> 00:25:50,083
I sold to the ISIS member at a
slightly higher price than the market

478
00:25:50,459 --> 00:25:53,918
For example, at the
beginning of their arrival here

479
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:55,918
There was no severe siege yet

480
00:25:56,626 --> 00:25:59,083
The selling price of a
cigarette was 1,500 or 2,000

481
00:25:59,334 --> 00:26:01,375
And I sold it to him
for 3,000 or 5,000

482
00:26:02,250 --> 00:26:05,959
Until the last
cigarette I sold to them

483
00:26:06,334 --> 00:26:07,542
One cigarette for 25,000

484
00:26:09,083 --> 00:26:10,918
I kept a personal
stock for myself

485
00:26:10,959 --> 00:26:13,876
I stopped selling because
I could no longer go out

486
00:26:14,209 --> 00:26:18,250
Because I used to bring them from
areas like Yarmouk, Tammuz, and Zanjili

487
00:26:18,542 --> 00:26:22,250
There was constant
bombing every time I went out

488
00:26:22,792 --> 00:26:23,876
I could not go out anymore

489
00:26:24,709 --> 00:26:28,709
And there were five or six
of us who smoked at home

490
00:26:29,542 --> 00:26:33,083
If I had not been selling
cigarettes and stocking up for us

491
00:26:34,125 --> 00:26:39,417
Our daily earnings from work
would have gone to buying cigarettes

492
00:26:39,918 --> 00:26:43,180
Interviewer: According to what you said, the price
of one cigarette was about 20 dollars at the time?

493
00:26:43,214 --> 00:26:45,255
Witness: Yes. Interviewer:
One cigarette? Witness: Yes

494
00:26:45,280 --> 00:26:48,709
As I told you, the
last pack I bought

495
00:26:48,959 --> 00:26:50,792
A full pack that
they sold wholesale

496
00:26:50,834 --> 00:26:52,918
Because wholesale
is different from retail

497
00:26:53,667 --> 00:26:54,918
The pack was 250,000

498
00:27:00,209 --> 00:27:02,959
When you went to the bathroom

499
00:27:03,375 --> 00:27:05,042
It was outside prayer times

500
00:27:06,375 --> 00:27:08,584
You would knock on
the door for the guard

501
00:27:08,626 --> 00:27:11,250
And tell him you want to go to
the bathroom so he opens the door

502
00:27:12,667 --> 00:27:14,584
During prayer times,
it got a little crowded

503
00:27:14,626 --> 00:27:16,334
You had to be quick

504
00:27:17,334 --> 00:27:21,167
So you did not delay those behind you from
praying, because they would be punished

505
00:27:21,876 --> 00:27:23,667
Especially during
the dawn prayer

506
00:27:23,709 --> 00:27:26,459
You had to be ready, and he would
wake you up an hour before prayer

507
00:27:27,125 --> 00:27:29,375
Until you finished ablution

508
00:27:30,250 --> 00:27:31,375
And went down to prayer

509
00:27:32,250 --> 00:27:33,876
Interviewer: How was
the water? Witness: Cold

510
00:27:34,459 --> 00:27:36,667
Interviewer: Was there soap or
cleaning supplies? Witness: Yes, soap

